  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Laws:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Federal Criminal Statutes:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\n3. State Laws:\nMany states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Define money laundering\n- Establish criminal penalties\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Impose reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n- Create mechanisms for investigating and prosecuting money laundering activities\n\nPenalties can include significant fines and imprisonment, with severity depending on the specific circumstances and amount of money involved.\n\nThe primary goal of these statutes is to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds and integrating them into the legitimate financial system.",
